From kevinushey at gmail.com  Thu Feb 13 19:29:30 2014
From: kevinushey at gmail.com (Kevin Ushey)
Date: Thu, 13 Feb 2014 10:29:30 -0800
Subject: [Rcpp-devel] conditionally created vectors
In-Reply-To: <FADB7D39-305A-4947-A0BB-D56832FEB346@gmail.com>
References: <9DF360CD-4FC7-4975-97B2-220B7D448C00@gmail.com>
 <21245.3124.193407.275794@max.nulle.part>
 <FADB7D39-305A-4947-A0BB-D56832FEB346@gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAJXgQP0GRX=wADgmWPiPeOc4Vw+Z4sYY-qXHTyopRfz7HQcLJw@mail.gmail.com>

The way around it is to declare 'xx' in the parent scope, and then assign
to it directly, e.g.

// [[Rcpp::export]]
Rcpp::NumericVector f1(String typ){
  Rcpp::NumericVector xx;
  if(typ=="nc"){
    xx = Rcpp::NumericVector(10);
  } else {
    xx = Rcpp::NumericVector(20);
  }
  return xx;
}

'Technically', the object 'xx' will be default initialized when declared
like that, but the compiler can optimize that away.

Cheers,
Kevin


